    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nRunning `vim.api.nvim_open_win` on startup still makes Neovim always enter and focus the leftmost window (it also generates a `BufEnter` event), which is confusing.\n\nThis is problematic for me, because [I’m creating empty buffers for padding](https://github.com/shortcuts/no-neck-pain.nvim/blob/5d91f31a2d583a367df97a4654be028fbe13f2d2/lua/no-neck-pain/ui.lua#L129) during startup and I don’t want them to have focus. It would be brittle to try to refocus on `BufEnter` events that are getting generated.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\n-- init.lua\nlocal side_buffer = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(--[[listed]] false,--[[scratch]] false)\nlocal side_win = vim.api.nvim_open_win(side_buffer, false, { split = \"left\", focusable = false })\n```\n\n1. Run:\n\n```shell\nnvim --clean -u init.lua init.lua\n```\n\nYou’ll see that the unnamed buffer (window) on the left has focus.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nFocus should be on the init.lua.\n\nAlternatively, there should be a way to specify which window should receive focus on startup. \nNaive `set_current_win` on startup doesn’t work. Deferring `set_current_win` after startup is not good, because it causes a flash of moving cursor from the padding buffer.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNot relevant, it’s a Lua API issue.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 15.1.1 (24B91)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nKitty 0.38.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nHomebrew",
